- The praetor, however, provided that many of the new actions which he introduced through the edict should lie only within an annus utilis from the moment at which they first accrued, though between this period and his own limited tenure oi office there does not seem to have been the connection suggested by Justinian in the text. By lar the most im· portant class ol these annales actiones are the praetorian penal actions, with the exception oi that on lurtum manifestum, which remained per- petua because it was in commutation of a capital penalty, Gaius iv. 111 ; iii. 189, but even these were perpetuae so far as they were brought only to deprive the delinquent of any benefit he had derived from his wrong : ‘in honorariis actionibus sic esse definiendum Cassius ait, ut quae rei persecutionem habeant, hae etiarn post annum darentur, ceterae intra annum' Dig. 44 7. 35. pr. Praetorian actions which were merely uni- laterally penal (e. g. actio doli) vvere prescribed in a year il contra ius civile, Dig. ib. Interdicts, so far as they were penal, were similarly limited: the actiones populares were all annales, Dig. 47. 23. 8: and the prescription oi the aedilician actions on sale has been already noticed‚ p. 423 supr.‚ as also has the longi temporis praescriptio relatingto actions lor the recovery ol property which had been for a defined time in the hands ol a bona fide possessor with iustus titulus, p. 217 supr. ln course ultime too a prescription was fixed by disconnected legislation lor other actions, in particular one ol five years sor the querella inofliciosi testamenti, Cod. 3. 28. 36. 2. Actione which fell under the old rule were called perpetuae, those which were limited by any oi these periods temporales.

More systematie legislation upon this matter commenced with Con· ' stantine, who enacted that all real actions which were not already limited might be repelled by an exceptio unless brought within lorty years, cod 7. 39. 2, which subsequently seems to have been reduced to thirty, the time here being not utile but continuum. In nn. 424 Theodosius sub- jected to this same thirty years’ limit all actions whatsoever‚ with a lew exceptione, which had hitherto been perpetuae, Cod. ib. 3. This rule is in lorce under Justinian, the only actions oi importance which are not governed by it being vindicatio in libertatem, Cod. 7. 22. 3, and fiscal claims ior unpaid taxes, Cod. 7. 39. 6, which continued perpetual in the old sense; so that in his compilations actio perpetua means an action which is prescribed in not less than thirty years.
